description: SAVE THE DATES Musicians demonstrate and explain the shared roots of diverse traditions from fascinating foreign and familiar cultures ranging from Kazakhstan to the Carolinas, from Brazil to Africa, China and Middle East. Dates: Feb 7, 22, 26. March 4, 13, 28. April 9, 25. Free except for performances Feb 26, Mar 28 and April 26, which require tickets. Live performances. Themes relate music to culture including Jazz, Islam, Women, Salsa, Polka, slavery, migration, languages, history, emotion, rent parties, courtship, how the medium of music illuminates difficult diversity issues. Artists include Eleanor Ellis, Phil Wiggins, Rick Franklin, Mike Baytop, Richard Miller and DC Choro, Benjamin Pasternack, Saïs Kamalidiin, Zarinah Shakir, Silk Road Dance, Wu Man, Dr. Fernando Rios, Ninety Miles. Details: http://www.nyumburu.umd.edu/events/Diversity%20through%20Music.pdf
title: Make Ours Music

description: Please join us for the "Academic Achievement: It's Not So Black and White" panel discussion on Thursday, April 18th, located in the Charles Carol Room in the Stamp Student Union from 12-2:00 pm. Four scholars will examine the questions of why gaps in academic achievement continue to persist among racial and ethnic groups and what may help to eliminate these gaps. UMD's own illustrious Dr. Patricia Hill Collins will moderate this discussion on academic achievement. The panelists include: Dr. Karl Alexander of Johns Hopkins Dr. Angel Harris of Princeton Dr. Michelle Espino of UMD's School of Education Dr. Odis Johnson of UMD's African American Studies Department
title: Academic Achievement: It's Not So Black and White

description: Come have Lunch with the Lawyer! Join the Graduate Student Legal Aid Office for the Life After F-1/J-1 Workshop with the Office of International Services. This workshop will be held on Tuesday, April 23, 2103 from 12:30PM to 1:30PM (lunch served at 12:15) in the Pyon Su Room, STAMP. Are you an F-1 or J-1 student planning to graduate within the next two years? Have you been wondering what employment options exist for you in the United States after graduation? The Graduate Student Legal Aid Office invites you to join us for a "Life After F-1/J-1" presentation by the Office of International Services. We will discuss a variety of employment visa options with a focus on F-1 OPT, J-1 student academic training and other J-1 categories, and the H-1B visa status. description: Rebels on Campus - Why Being a Liberal on the College Campus is Really Boring UMD Republicans is proud to host New York Times bestselling author and journalist Katie Pavlich through the Clare Boothe Luce Policy Institute. She will be lecturing on political activism on the college campus - and why being a young liberal today isn't so unique. The lecture will take place on April 30th at 7PM in the Grand Ballroom Lounge of Stamp. This event is free and open to the public - and will include a short Q&A session following the lecture. Pavlich is the news editor for Townhall.com and contributing editor to Townhall Magazine. Her commentary has been featured on Fox News, CNN, MSNBC, and CNBC.
title: UMD College Republicans: Katie Pavlich Lecture
